article.description:
If Pat Garrity can hit a 3-pointer, he can
make a game-winning shot, too.
article.headline: Orlando adds to its edge over 76ers in standings

images.name: Garrity_Pat 020317 horz inline
images.caption: 17 Mar 2002:  Pat Garrity #8 of the Orlando Magic makes the game winning shot against the Philadelphia 76ers with 19 seconds left on the clock at the First Union Center in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. The Magic won 105-103. DIGITAL IMAGE. Note to user: Use

article.linkText: Inside, outside, Garrity gets it done for Magic
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- If Pat Garrity can hit a 3-pointer, he can make a game-winning shot, too. Garrity's running jumper with 16.7 seconds left lifted the Orlando Magic to their sixth consecutive victory over the Philadelphia 76ers 105-103 on Sunday. It was the fifth victory in a row for Orlando after four consecutive defeats and moved the Magic 1½ games ahead of Philadelphia for the No. 5 spot in the Eastern Conference. The defending Eastern Conference champions have lost two consecutive after winning seven of eight. The Magic took a 103-101 lead on back-to-back 3-pointers by McGrady and Garrity with 53.1 seconds left. After Corie Blount hit two free throws to tie it, Garrity gave the Magic the lead for good. Iverson and Snow both missed shots that would've tied it in the final seconds. Before Garrity's 3, Orlando coach Doc Rivers asked him if he could hit one from beyond the arc. "I thought it was a funny question," said Garrity, who leads the team with a 41.9 shooting percentage from 3-point range. "I said, 'Yeah.' So he drew up the play." Garrity wasn't looking for a 3 to break the tie. He expected the Sixers to use their last foul. "That wasn't the play we drew up," Garrity said. "But McGrady went one-on-one and my guy went over to double, and left me open. He flipped it back, I saw an open lane, put it on the floor and floated it up there." McGrady had 29 points and a career-high 13 assists, and Troy Hudson scored 19 off the bench for Orlando. Garrity scored 13 of his 18 points in the second half. Allen Iverson had 39 points and 10 assists, and Eric Snow added 20 points for Philadelphia, which lost for the first time in 15 games when scoring more than 100 points this season. "I felt we had this one," Iverson said. "We were in position to win and we just didn't do it." McGrady, who recorded his first career triple-double in a victory over the Sixers last month, shot 3-for-10, and missed five of nine free throws in the first half. But he finished 11-for-25. "I was rusty in the first half so I had to get other guys involved, play defense and rebound," McGrady said. Hudson, who had 58 points in the previous two games, hit his first eight shots, and had 14 points in the second quarter. Darrell Armstrong added 15 points and harassed Iverson most of the afternoon on defense. After trailing most of the second half, the Sixers took a 95-94 lead on a jumper by Iverson with 5:33 left. Horace Grant then hit a 20-footer for Orlando, but Snow answered with a jumper and Blount got a fastbreak layup off a pass from Iverson to make it 99-96. Another jumper by Snow gave the Sixers a 101-97 lead, before McGrady and Garrity hit their 3s. The Sixers were without forward Matt Harpring and guard Aaron McKie. Harpring, who along with Mutombo had started every game, had a stomach virus. McKie, winner of the Sixth Man award last year, has missed 20 of the last 23 games because of a left ankle sprain. "We didn't make the last four of five shots," Sixers coach Larry Brown said. "I don't know how you're going to win a game like that." Orlando outscored the Sixers 15-5 to start the second quarter, taking its biggest lead, 44-35, on a 3-pointer by Hudson. Philadelphia went on a 9-3 run to close within 55-54 at halftime. Iverson scored all nine of the points, including a 3-pointer that capped the run. Game notes
Orlando is 35-16 against the Sixers, including 3-0 this season. ... Orlando is 4-0 without Mike Miller, the team's second-leading scorer, who is out with a sprained left ankle. ... McGrady has 168 points in the Magic's last five games, including a career-high 50-point effort against the Wizards on March 8. ... Derrick Coleman had nine points after recording back-to-back 20-point games returning from knee injury. ... Raja Bell, starting for Harpring, had four points. Iverson, who shot 14-for-33, just missed his fifth 40-point game in the last 10. He has scored 30 or more a league-high 33 times this season.
